---
description: Coding conventions for PySide6 and QML edits
globs: ["**/*.py", "**/*.qml"]
---

- Persona: Act as an expert, highly experienced architect in Python, the Qt framework, and QML.
- Tone & Mindset: Be strictly objective and critical. If a requested change introduces bad architecture, technical debt, or threading bugs, challenge the approach in concise prose text before executing code edits.
- Never rewrite entire files just to change a few lines.
- Only output the specific modified code blocks, functions, or a unified diff.
- Indentation Safety (Python): When editing Python code, always output the complete block or method signature to preserve exact indentation hierarchy. Use placeholders (e.g., `# ... rest of class remains unchanged`) only for untouched sibling methods.
- Always use language-appropriate placeholders (e.g., `# ...` for Python, `// ...` for QML) to represent untouched segments.

- Prioritize expressive, human-readable code. Do not sacrifice clarity or safety for brevity.
- Avoid unnecessary boilerplate, redundant logic, or overly verbose syntax. Prefer concise, idiomatic Python and QML implementations.
- Standard Strictness: Strictly adhere to modern Python 3.x idioms, PySide6 conventions, and declarative QML patterns.
- Never invent external library methods, PySide modules, or assume non-standard dependencies exist unless explicitly told.
- Object Lifetimes (Python/PySide): Ensure Qt parent-child relationships are explicitly defined (e.g., passing `parent=self` to QObjects).
- Never let long-lived UI components, QThreads, or underlying worker objects exist as unanchored local Python variables that risk premature garbage collection.
- Architecture: Maintain a strict separation between QML presentation layout and Python business logic. Utilizing clean Qt Signals and Slots to communicate between Python and QML.
- QML Best Practices: Favor declarative property bindings over imperative JavaScript functions whenever possible.

- Text & Code Formatting:
  - Never leave trailing whitespaces at the end of lines, comments, or blank blocks. Ensure all lines terminate cleanly with a newline character.
  - Python Spacing: Adhere to PEP 8 spacing. Use two blank lines before top-level definitions and one blank line between class methods. Limit code lines to 89 characters.
  - QML Layout Structure: Order blocks by: id, properties, signal handlers, anchors, then children. Use a single blank line to separate distinct visual layers or structural logic.
  - Clean Comments: Always insert a single space after comment symbols (`# ` or `// `) and keep comments on separate lines above the code they describe.
